ce:section.ce:para:
To assess the sensing efficiency of synthesized nanomaterials, namely BPGQDs, NaV and BPGQD/NaV were exposed to 110 nM of rutin. The photoluminescence (PL) emission intensities were analyzed to quantify the degree of quenching for each nanomaterials (refer to Fig. 7
                        ). Fig. 7a shows the PL emission behavior of BPGQDs with the addition of rutin and observed that no significant changes in PL intensity. Similarly, Fig. 7b shows the PL emission behavior of NaV with rutin and found that some quenching were noted as compared to BPGQDs and maximum quenching of rutin was observed with BPGQDs@NaV as shown in Fig. 7c. As anticipated and depicted in Fig. 7d, the greatest quenching extent (F0
                        F)/F0, (where F represents the fluorescence intensity with the presence of rutin and F0 is the initial intensity) was observed in BPGQD/NaV consistent with the previously outlined mechanisms.
